E-C-2, the virtual server.

You have an application, and you need a computer, reachable from the internet, to run it on. Just one machine, your code on it, and a U-R-L you can open in a browser. That machine is an E-C-2 instance. E-C-2, which stands for Elastic Compute Cloud, is AWS's virtual server service, and it's the most fundamental compute primitive on AWS. Almost every workload runs on E-C-2 in some form, either directly, or as the engine behind a managed service.

An instance is a virtual machine. AWS picks the physical hardware, runs a hypervisor on it, and gives you a slice. You choose the operating system, the C-P-U, the memory, the storage, and the networking, and AWS handles everything underneath.

Getting from nothing to a server you can open in a browser comes down to six decisions. An A-M-I, the disk image to boot from. An instance type, which is the size. A key pair, so you can log in. The network, meaning a V-P-C and a public I-P. A security group, which is the firewall; you open port eighty for H-T-T-P and port twenty-two for S-S-H. And user data, a boot script that turns a bare operating system into a running app. Make the happy-path choice for each, and you get your "it works" moment.

The rest of this module revisits each of those six decisions with real judgment, and then scales the pattern out: from one instance, to a load balancer in front of many, to an Auto Scaling Group that grows and shrinks the fleet automatically.
